  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_733869558" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/733869558" />
    <a title="Michelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3733115-michelle"><img alt="Michelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578110160p2/3733115.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/733869558?book_show_action=true">Oct 04, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle" href="/user/show/3733115-michelle">Michelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer733869558" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4387643184590970009">There is a very good review of this in the New York Times, which echoes my own discomfort with the book. Which are Naoki&apos;s words and which are David Mitchell&apos;s? I haven&apos;t read any of Mitchell&apos;s writing, so I don&apos;t know his style. And I can&apos;t speak another language, so I can&apos;t comprehend what changes may be normally made without the translater totally altering the original idea. But some things didnt ring true, and that saddened me, because I&apos;d hoped for some answers that may help me with my auti</span>
  <span id="freeText4387643184590970009" style="display:none">There is a very good review of this in the New York Times, which echoes my own discomfort with the book. Which are Naoki's words and which are David Mitchell's? I haven't read any of Mitchell's writing, so I don't know his style. And I can't speak another language, so I can't comprehend what changes may be normally made without the translater totally altering the original idea. But some things didnt ring true, and that saddened me, because I'd hoped for some answers that may help me with my autistic child.<br /><br />Like Naoki, my child is barely verbal. A lot of the questions about behaviour in the book could be directed at my child - the fuss over little mistakes; the jumping; the love of TV adverts; doing what you've been told not to countless times. The explanations Naoki gives for the above make sense. But how has Naoki learned some of the concepts that are written in this book? For example, talking about his love of water "we just want to go back...To a primeval era..aquatic life-forms came Into being and evolved..." How does anyone learn about evolution, or primeval eras? You read about them, you ask questions and people explain, you watch a tv documentary. But how can a child with a simple vocabulary of spoken words, and who prefers simple picture books learn about these concepts? How did his mum know to read to him or teach him these concepts of evolution?<br /><br />Since reading the book I've talked less baby talk to my 11 year old, and tried to be more tolerant of the squealing, which he does constantly despite being to,d constantly told not to do so. But if Naoki is to be believed, just can't stop himself. However I struggle with the difficulties of abstract concepts and explanations to give My son. When there was a power cut, I found that difficult to explain. Does my son understand electricity? That it's the same word as power? That the electricity flows through the power sockets and plugs, and now has stopped? When he said "scissors" I thought "well, power CUT, that's why he is saying scissors". But do I keep trying with the explanation, assuming there's a genius inside like Naoki? Or do I take it at face value, that he has made a word association and Not understood an abstract concept and simplify the explanation?<br /><br /><br />I haven't got any answers. I'll reread the book, still with a touch of cynicism and incredulity, but try and modify some of my dealings with my beloved so.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4387643184590970009" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

